{
  "stem": "10572.6",
  "chunk_idx": 0,
  "model": "openai/gpt-oss-120b",
  "elapsed_s": 9.3,
  "sentences_input": [
    {
      "segment_idx": 0,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 0,
      "text": "You know, it's actually January 15th.",
      "word_count": 6
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 1,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 0,
      "text": "January 15th,--",
      "word_count": 2
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 2,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 0,
      "text": "--1996.",
      "word_count": 1
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 3,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 0,
      "text": "When-- when we finally left Germany on that 23rd of June, 1939, and my parents and my younger sister took us to the train, and it was this bloodletting experience that we had experienced so often of saying farewell without knowing if you would ever see them again, if they would ever see us again.",
      "word_count": 55
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 3,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 1,
      "text": "And I still see the-- [PAUSES FOR 3 SECONDS] --the white handkerchiefs, you know, disappearing.",
      "word_count": 15
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 3,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 2,
      "text": "And-- but we somehow felt that we were getting closer to the possibility of getting my parents and my younger sister out.",
      "word_count": 22
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 3,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 3,
      "text": "And we went to-- we went to a-- to a-- to the border, Aachen.",
      "word_count": 14
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 3,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 4,
      "text": "Aachen was the border before we got into Belgium on our way to England.",
      "word_count": 14
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 3,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 5,
      "text": "And in Aachen, we were taken off the train-- all of the people that were going to the Lord Kitchener Camp-- for final examination.",
      "word_count": 24
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 3,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 6,
      "text": "And after they-- after the Nazis had stolen, robbed, thieved everything we ever owned, here we were going through an examination, where we-- the most unbelievable examination I've ever gone through, where we had to undress and we had to bend over.",
      "word_count": 42
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 3,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 7,
      "text": "They wanted to see if we had hidden diamonds.",
      "word_count": 9
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 3,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 8,
      "text": "And we were checked out.",
      "word_count": 5
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 3,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 9,
      "text": "And I felt later on that they had saved no effort to make our leaving Germany as easy as possible for us.",
      "word_count": 22
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 3,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 10,
      "text": "And we couldn't wait.",
      "word_count": 4
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 3,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 11,
      "text": "And then we went through Belgium, and we arrived in England.",
      "word_count": 11
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 3,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 12,
      "text": "We saw the White Cliffs of Dover in contrast to all the darkness and blackness that we left behind.",
      "word_count": 19
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 3,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 13,
      "text": "And we met these wonderful people, and I have always been fond and grateful for the unbelievable hospitality that the English offered us.",
      "word_count": 23
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 4,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 0,
      "text": "And in the Lord Kitchener Camp-- the camp was self sufficient.",
      "word_count": 11
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 4,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 1,
      "text": "We had to do-- we either work in the kitchen or work in the camp university or do whatever or rebuild.",
      "word_count": 21
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 4,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 2,
      "text": "And we had to rebuild the roads.",
      "word_count": 7
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 4,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 3,
      "text": "And it seemed to me that one of the toughest jobs was doing the concrete work of building roads.",
      "word_count": 19
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 4,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 4,
      "text": "And since I didn't know yet how tough I had to be in order to survive in the United States, I picked this and volunteered.",
      "word_count": 25
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 4,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 5,
      "text": "There weren't many volunteers for that, building roads, concrete roads.",
      "word_count": 10
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 4,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 6,
      "text": "And we had a-- we had a man who was in charge of building roads.",
      "word_count": 15
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 4,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 7,
      "text": "He was a former architect from Germany by the name of Herz.",
      "word_count": 12
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 4,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 8,
      "text": "And some of the roads were-- kept water after every rain.",
      "word_count": 11
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 4,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 9,
      "text": "And there was a [INAUDIBLE] in the camp that was saying, you don't need brain to build the roads as long as you have Herz, 'herz' being 'heart.' And there was-- again, there was lots of tension in the camp because of the horrible fears that we had for our beloved ones that we left home.",
      "word_count": 56
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 4,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 10,
      "text": "And you became-- because after the war broke out after the first of September, there was a complete cut-off.",
      "word_count": 19
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 4,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 11,
      "text": "We had no more communications.",
      "word_count": 5
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 4,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 12,
      "text": "We didn't know if my parents were still there or if they were on their way to Auschwitz or that sort.",
      "word_count": 21
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 4,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 13,
      "text": "At that time we didn't know about Auschwitz.",
      "word_count": 8
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 4,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 14,
      "text": "Auschwitz didn't exist then, but whatever.",
      "word_count": 6
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 4,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 15,
      "text": "And I couldn't stand it.",
      "word_count": 5
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 4,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 16,
      "text": "I couldn't sleep at night.",
      "word_count": 5
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 4,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 17,
      "text": "And I started to realize there was one possibility.",
      "word_count": 9
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 4,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 18,
      "text": "We had good, good friends in Denmark.",
      "word_count": 7
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 4,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 19,
      "text": "A Danish girl had spent two summers as an exchange student at our house and tried-- she and her husband, who was a pastor, tried to get us out of Germany before the war broke out and didn't succeed.",
      "word_count": 39
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 4,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 20,
      "text": "But I wrote my letters to my parents to Crystal Merch in Denmark.",
      "word_count": 13
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 4,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 21,
      "text": "And she would take them out of my English envelope and put them in a Danish envelope and then send them to my parents.",
      "word_count": 24
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 4,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 22,
      "text": "And my parents would correspond the same way.",
      "word_count": 8
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 4,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 23,
      "text": "And this way, we were in contact, even though greatly delayed by two senders and by all kinds of other-- but it helped us.",
      "word_count": 24
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 4,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 24,
      "text": "And then, as I said before, on the-- the-- the end of April, I went to the American Embassy.",
      "word_count": 19
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 4,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 25,
      "text": "And I passed, and I got my-- the most important stamp I ever saw, the most important paper, my passport with the immigration visa.",
      "word_count": 24
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 5,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 0,
      "text": "1940.",
      "word_count": 1
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 5,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 1,
      "text": "And as I left the embassy, there were newspaper photographers standing there with their cameras aimed at the exit.",
      "word_count": 19
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 5,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 2,
      "text": "And I wasn't surprised at all that they were there to take the picture of the happiest guy in the world.",
      "word_count": 21
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 5,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 3,
      "text": "I was a little bit disappointed to realize that they didn't wait for me.",
      "word_count": 14
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 5,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 4,
      "text": "They waited for some know-wells, the American Under Secretary of State, who also happened to be in the embassy that day.",
      "word_count": 21
    }
  ],
